      </div>

      <div class="prose-dark mt-8">
        <p>
          The most frequently missed technical practice is AI crawler access. Many sites that blocked GPTBot and similar user-agents in 2023–2024 as a training-data defence measure are still blocking citation retrieval today. The same bots that scrape training data also drive retrieval-augmented generation — they cannot be separated. If earning AI citations is your objective, you must allow these crawlers. Review your robots.txt and add explicit allow directives for GPTBot, PerplexityBot, ClaudeBot, and Bingbot.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Voice Search Practices -->
      <div class="prose-dark mt-16">
        <h2 id="voice-practices" class="anchor-top">Voice Search AEO Practices</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>Voice search operates on a single-answer model that makes AEO selection binary: you are either the answer or you are invisible.</strong> When a user asks Siri, Alexa, or Google Assistant a question, the assistant selects one source and reads one answer. There is no "position two." This makes voice search the highest-stakes AEO surface and the one where structural practices have the most direct impact on visibility.
        </p>

        <h3>Answer Length for Voice</h3>
        <p>
          Voice assistants do not read extended passages. The optimal answer length for voice extraction is 30–50 words — enough to be a complete, standalone response, short enough to be read in ten to fifteen seconds without the listener losing context. Write voice-target answers as complete sentences that begin with the subject of the query: "Featured snippets are excerpts…" rather than "In answer to your question about featured snippets…"
        </p>

        <h3>Conversational Query Matching</h3>
        <p>
          Voice queries are an average of 6–8 words longer than typed queries and almost always phrased as natural-language questions. Target these longer-form questions explicitly. "What is the best way to optimise for voice search?" is a more realistic voice query than "voice search optimisation." Use Google autocomplete and People Also Ask results for voice-intent queries to identify the exact phrasing your audience uses.
        </p>

        <h3>Local Voice Search</h3>
        <p>
          A significant proportion of voice queries carry local intent: "best AEO agency near me," "who does answer engine optimisation in London." For brands serving a geographic area, local AEO requires a complete and accurate Google Business Profile, LocalBusiness schema, and content that explicitly mentions the service area. Local voice queries have high purchase intent — being the voice answer for these queries has direct commercial value.
        </p>

        <h3>Speakable Schema</h3>
        <p>
          The Speakable schema type allows you to explicitly mark passages designed for voice extraction. While Google Assistant support for Speakable is currently limited to news publishers, the schema is forward-compatible — implementing it now positions your content for expanded platform support as voice AEO matures. Mark paragraphs that contain your most concise, conversationally-phrased answers.
        </p>
      </div>

